\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.1}{\ignorespaces Attestix Protocol module architecture (native LaTeX/TikZ rendering). The four domain projects (top) each instantiate the parameterised \texttt {AttestixManager} from \texttt {shared/attestix\_client.py}, which wraps the nine service modules in the pip-installed \texttt {attestix} package. All cryptographic artefacts are persisted to the local JSON store under \texttt {\textasciitilde /.attestix/}. The security middleware intercepts agent calls flowing from the five orchestration frameworks at the bottom.}}{14}{figure.caption.13}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces Hospital regulated run: identity provisioning for all 4 agents, EU AI Act compliance profile generation, and W3C Verifiable Credential issuance (Phase 1 --- LangChain intake with vertical symptoms output).}}{16}{figure.caption.16}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.3}{\ignorespaces Hospital regulated run: UCAN delegation gates for all three handoffs (Phase 2 DB, Phase 3 CrewAI, Phase 4 CMO) showing capability verification, conformity gatekeeping, and Merkle provenance logging per agent.}}{18}{figure.caption.18}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces Unregulated baseline run (no Attestix): Phase 1 LangChain intake and Phase 2 Enterprise DB with no security gates, no delegation verification, and no provenance logging.}}{20}{figure.caption.20}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.5}{\ignorespaces Hospital regulated run: secure final diagnosis and treatment plan issued by the Chief Medical Officer, with Contrast Dye allergy flagged and no fatal drug interactions identified.}}{21}{figure.caption.21}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.6}{\ignorespaces Cryptographic audit trail (4-entry SHA-256 hash chain) for the regulated Hospital pipeline, captured from a fresh live run on 2026-05-13 with the patched code on AWS Bedrock \texttt {us.meta.llama3-3-70b-instruct-v1:0}. Each agent maintains its own per-agent chain (every entry is GENESIS within its agent's log); cross-agent provenance is established via the UCAN delegation token captured in each entry's \texttt {decision\_rationale}. The blockchain anchor record below uses the previously verified on-chain transaction \texttt {0x107aa293...7963f} and EAS attestation UID \texttt {0xb2cdbd85...} on Base Sepolia, independently inspectable at \url {https://sepolia.basescan.org/tx/0x107aa293eea834a69d3fc7ff8bc3202e2608704184a9e9d9fd7fa3df5df7963f}.}}{22}{figure.caption.22}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.7}{\ignorespaces EAS attestation record on Base Sepolia confirming the hospital audit trail anchor (UID: \texttt {0xb2cdbd8583f4d2afc57...})}}{23}{figure.caption.24}%
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.8}{\ignorespaces BaseScan wallet history: schema registration (block 41364881), two reverted attest transactions due to insufficient gas limit, and the final successful anchoring (block 41365382)}}{23}{figure.caption.25}%
